<p>Network data from NetBlocks confirm that internet service has been cut on multiple internet providers in Gabon on Saturday 26 August 2023, the day of presidential and legislative elections. A <a href="https://twitter.com/netblocks/status/1696881683348295776" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">gradual restoration</a> was observed through Wednesday, 30 August, after military officers announced they had taken power to end the incumbent president’s leadership.</p>
<p>The restrictions are likely to limit the free flow of information online, presenting a challenge to election transparency as polls are held and votes counted as President Ali Bongo seeks to continue his family’s 56-year long tenure in power.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>⚠️ Confirmed: Live network data show a nation-scale internet blackout is now in effect across <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/Gabon?src=hash&amp;ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">#Gabon</a> on election day; authorities claim the measure is intended to &#34;prevent the spread of calls for violence&#34; as a curfew is imposed 📉</p>
